\title{Severity of Koide-type quark mass relations\\under look-elsewhere correction}
\author{Andrew M.~Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m_i)/(\sum \sqrt{m_i})^2 = 2/3$, observed for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$, has motivated numerous extensions to the quark sector over the past four decades. These extensions typically introduce additional degrees of freedom beyond the original formula---evaluating masses at non-self renormalization scales, allowing signed square roots, or searching across multiple quark triples---and report closures of varying tightness without a systematic accounting of how each degree of freedom affects the false-positive rate.

This note attempts such an accounting. We enumerate all $\binom{6}{3} = 20$ quark-only three-fermion combinations, define a physically motivated discrete search space of evaluation scales, and compute $Q$ for every combination of triple, sign pattern, and scale assignment---11{,}208 trials in total. We then apply the same search to $10{,}000$ Monte Carlo pseudo-experiments with random masses drawn from the Standard Model quark mass range and compare the observed results to the null distribution at each level of search freedom.

The evaluation-scale degree of freedom (QCD running to non-self scales) is identified as the specific parameter that degrades test severity. At full search freedom, random data produces results indistinguishable from real data ($p = 0.49$). However, claims that pre-specify the triple and sign pattern before computation survive with $p < 0.01$, as does the Descartes/Soddy geometric construction linking the lepton outer Soddy curvature to the strange quark mass ($p = 0.004$). A severity ranking of published and testable Koide-type claims is presented.

\smallskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Koide relation; look-elsewhere effect; severity testing; quark mass relations; statistical significance
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Koide~\citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} observed that the charged lepton pole masses satisfy
\begin{equation}
Q(e, \mu, \tau) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
to a residual of approximately $6 \times 10^{-6}$. This relation has no accepted derivation from the Standard Model, yet its numerical precision has sustained interest for over forty years.

Extensions to the quark sector include Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011}, who observed that the triple $(s, c, b)$ with a sign-flipped $\sqrt{m_s}$ approaches $Q = 2/3$; Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011}, who surveyed multiple quark triples; Cao~\citep{Cao2012}, who examined the $(c, b, t)$ triple at self-scales; and Brilliant~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, who reported that the $(c, b, t)$ combination closes within propagated input uncertainty when $m_c$ is evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ via four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running. Each extension introduces degrees of freedom not present in the original lepton observation: the choice of which triple to examine, whether to allow signed square roots, and at what renormalization scale to evaluate each mass.

The central question of this note is: \textbf{given the degrees of freedom each claim uses, how often would random data produce an equally tight closure?} This is the look-elsewhere effect~(LEE), well-studied in resonance searches~\citep{GrossVitells2010}. What appears to be absent from the Koide literature is a systematic application of LEE analysis to mass-relation claims. We attempt to fill this gap, with the caveat that our analysis covers only the specific search spaces we define and should not be read as exhaustive over all possible formulations.


\subsection{Scope}

This note does:
\begin{itemize}
\item Enumerate all quark-only Koide triples and compute $Q$ at every combination of sign pattern and physically motivated evaluation scale;
\item Define the search space before computation and document the selection criteria;
\item Apply the same search to Monte Carlo pseudo-experiments to establish a null distribution;
\item Isolate each degree of freedom individually;
\item Rank published claims by severity~\citep{Mayo1996,MayoSpanos2006}.
\end{itemize}

This note does not claim to have tested all possible formulations, make any claim about physical origin, or address the lepton Koide itself beyond using it as a reference point.


\subsection{Severity testing}

We adopt the severity framework of Mayo~\citep{Mayo1996} and Mayo and Spanos~\citep{MayoSpanos2006}. A claim $C$ passes a severe test $T$ if
\begin{equation}
\text{SEV}(C, T) \;=\; P\!\left(\text{$T$ would not produce a result this extreme} \;\big|\; \text{$C$ is false}\right)
\end{equation}
is high. In our analysis, ``$C$ is false'' corresponds to the null hypothesis that quark masses have no Koide structure, implemented as random masses drawn from the same range. Severity $= 1 - p$, where $p$ is the fraction of null pseudo-experiments producing a result as tight as observed.


\section{Search space}
\label{sec:space}

\subsection{Inputs}

We use $\overline{\text{MS}}$ quark masses from FLAG~2024~\citep{FLAG2024} ($N_f = 2+1+1$ lattice averages) and PDG~2024~\citep{PDG2024}:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
Quark & Mass & Source \\
\midrule
$m_u(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $2.16 \pm 0.10$ MeV & FLAG 2024 \\
$m_d(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $4.70 \pm 0.05$ MeV & FLAG 2024 \\
$m_s(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $93.4 \pm 0.8$ MeV & FLAG 2024 \\
$m_c(m_c)$ & $1280.7 \pm 1.3$ MeV & FLAG 2024 \\
$m_b(m_b)$ & $4203 \pm 11$ MeV & FLAG 2024 \\
$m_t(m_t)$ & $162.5 \pm 0.7$ GeV & PDG 2024 (MS-bar) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Running is performed at four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ and full threshold matching. The propagated uncertainty on $Q$ is $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$, dominated by $m_t$.


\subsection{Evaluation scales}

Each quark mass may be evaluated at its $\overline{\text{MS}}$ self-scale or at the mass of any Standard Model particle (or simple additive combination) within its perturbative running window:
\begin{align*}
\text{Charm:} &\quad [m_c(m_c),\; m_b(m_b)] = [1.281,\; 4.203]\;\text{GeV} \\
\text{Bottom:} &\quad [m_b(m_b),\; m_t(m_t)] = [4.203,\; 162.5]\;\text{GeV} \\
\text{Top:} &\quad \text{self-scale only (decays before hadronizing)}
\end{align*}
Light quarks ($u, d, s$) have no perturbative self-scale and are evaluated only at physical scales within the charm running window. Round-number conventions ($1$~GeV, $2$~GeV) are excluded. The complete scale list is archived as \texttt{search\_space.json} in the accompanying repository~\citep{RepoMC}.

This search space is intentionally permissive: it encompasses the scale choices made in all published Koide-type quark claims known to us. The resulting false-positive rates are therefore conservative---a smaller search space would produce lower $p$-values for surviving claims.


\subsection{Sign patterns and trial count}

For each triple $(m_1, m_2, m_3)$ we test four sign patterns: $(+,+,+)$, $(-,+,+)$, $(+,-,+)$, $(+,+,-)$. The total search space at maximum freedom is $20 \times 4 \times (\text{scales}) = 12{,}960$ trials.


\section{Observed results}
\label{sec:results}

Of the 12{,}960 trials, 8 produce $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q$ (sub-$1\sigma$ closures). These occur in exactly three triples:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llllcr}
\toprule
Triple & Scales & Signs & $Q$ & $|Q - 2/3|$ & $n\sigma$ \\
\midrule
$(c,b,t)$ & $c@m_\tau$, $b@$self, $t@$self & $(+,+,+)$ & $0.66672$ & $5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.09$ \\
$(s,c,b)$ & $s@2m_\tau$, $c@m_\tau$, $b@m_H$ & $(-,+,+)$ & $0.66674$ & $6.9 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.13$ \\
$(u,s,c)$ & $u@(m_\tau{+}m_c)$, $s@m_c$, $c@m_b$ & $(-,+,+)$ & $0.66658$ & $9.0 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.17$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Tightest closure per triple (one representative hit each; additional sub-$1\sigma$ hits in $(s,c,b)$ and $(c,b,t)$ are listed in the repository). The remaining 17 triples produce zero sub-$3\sigma$ hits across 9{,}648 trials.}
\label{tab:hits}
\end{table}


\section{Monte Carlo null test}
\label{sec:mc}

For each pseudo-experiment, six masses are drawn log-uniformly from $[2\;\text{MeV},\; 170\;\text{GeV}]$, sorted, and assigned to the same slot structure as the real quarks. Surrogate QCD running is applied: the same multiplicative mass ratios computed from real four-loop QCD at each evaluation scale are applied to the random masses, preserving the search-space structure. We generate $10{,}000$ pseudo-experiments per test configuration.


\section{Isolating degrees of freedom}
\label{sec:isolation}

\subsection{Phase 1: which knob inflates the noise?}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrrr}
\toprule
Test & Trials & Observed best & MC median best & $p$ \\
\midrule
A: Signs only & 80 & $4.65 \times 10^{-3}$ & $7.16 \times 10^{-3}$ & $0.38$ \\
B: Running only & 3{,}240 & $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & $1.77 \times 10^{-4}$ & $0.28$ \\
C: Signs + running & 12{,}960 & $5.10 \times 10^{-5}$ & $5.20 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.49$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Phase~1: isolating each degree of freedom. The evaluation-scale degree of freedom (running) is the primary source of false positives. Sign freedom alone does not materially inflate the noise. See also Figure~\ref{fig:phase1}.}
\label{tab:phase1}
\end{table}


\subsection{Phase 2: severity ranking}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/phase1_isolate.pdf}
\caption{Phase~1: isolating degrees of freedom. Each panel shows the distribution of the best $|Q - 2/3|$ across $10{,}000$ Monte Carlo pseudo-experiments (blue histogram) versus the observed value from real quark masses (red dashed line). \emph{Left:} signs only (80 trials). \emph{Center:} running only (3{,}240 trials). \emph{Right:} signs and running combined (12{,}960 trials). The observed result moves from the tail to the center of the null distribution as running is added, identifying the evaluation-scale degree of freedom as the primary source of false positives.}
\label{fig:phase1}
\end{figure}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrcccc}
\toprule
Claim & Trials & Obs.\ best & MC median & $p$ & Severity \\
\midrule
Lepton Soddy $L^2 \to m_s$ (no running) & $(*)$ & $0.10\%$ & $59\%$ & $0.004$ & $0.996$ \\
$(c,b,t)$ $(+,+,+)$ + running, pre-specified & 54 & $5.1{\times}10^{-5}$ & $0.20$ & $0.005$ & $0.995$ \\
$(c,b,t)$ self-scale $(+,+,+)$ & 1 & $4.7{\times}10^{-3}$ & $0.23$ & $0.006$ & $0.994$ \\
Lepton Soddy $L^2 \to m_s$ (with running) & $(*)$ & $0.10\%$ & --- & $0.007$ & $0.993$ \\
$(c,b,t)$ all signs + running & 216 & $5.1{\times}10^{-5}$ & $0.10$ & $0.011$ & $0.989$ \\
$(s,c,b)$ signed, self-scale~\citep{Rivero2011} & 4 & $7.5{\times}10^{-3}$ & $0.14$ & $0.030$ & $0.970$ \\
Adjacent chain, sign rule, no running & 3 & $4.7{\times}10^{-3}$ & $0.067$ & $0.039$ & $0.961$ \\
\midrule
Adjacent chain, sign rule + running & 594 & $5.1{\times}10^{-5}$ & $0.037$ & $0.074$ & $0.926$ \\
Adjacent chain, all signs + running & 2{,}376 & $5.1{\times}10^{-5}$ & $0.014$ & $0.109$ & $0.891$ \\
20 triples, self-scale $(+,+,+)$ & 20 & $4.7{\times}10^{-3}$ & $0.015$ & $0.207$ & $0.793$ \\
Full search (all knobs) & 12{,}960 & $5.1{\times}10^{-5}$ & $5.3{\times}10^{-5}$ & $0.489$ & $0.511$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Severity ranking of Koide-type claims. Horizontal rule separates claims surviving at $p < 0.05$ (above) from those that do not (below). The Descartes/Soddy tests (marked $*$) use a different structure described in Section~\ref{sec:descartes}. MC: $10{,}000$ pseudo-experiments per configuration.}
\label{tab:severity}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/significance_ranking.pdf}
\caption{Severity ranking of all tested Koide-type claims, sorted by $p$-value. Green: $p < 0.01$. Yellow: $p < 0.05$. Orange: $p < 0.10$. Red: not significant. The severity cliff lies between pre-specified single-triple claims (which survive) and multi-triple searches (which do not). Data from Table~\ref{tab:severity}.}
\label{fig:ranking}
\end{figure}


\section{The Descartes extension}
\label{sec:descartes}

The Descartes circle theorem, applied to the Koide-saturating lepton triple following Kocik~\citep{Kocik2012}, produces an outer Soddy curvature
\begin{equation}
L \;=\; \sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau} \;-\; \sqrt{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau} \;\approx\; 9.753\;\text{MeV}^{1/2}
\end{equation}
whose square $L^2 = 95.12$~MeV matches the strange quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the lepton-sum scale $m_s(\Sigma m_\ell) = 95.02$~MeV to $0.10\%$.

This construction has near-zero degrees of freedom: the triple is the unique charged lepton triple, the Soddy curvature is determined by the Descartes geometry, $L^2$ is determined, and the match is to a specific quark at a specific scale.

We test this via $100{,}000$ pseudo-experiments: three random ``lepton'' masses and six random ``quark'' masses drawn log-uniformly. Among draws where the three leptons satisfy $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-3}$, we compute $L^2$ and check whether it matches any of the six quark masses to within $0.10\%$. The fraction of null experiments achieving this is $p = 0.004$ without running on the quarks and $p = 0.007$--$0.012$ with surrogate running factors. Both are significant at the $1\%$ level (Figure~\ref{fig:descartes}).

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/phase3b_lepton_soddy.pdf}
\caption{Descartes/Soddy test. \emph{Left:} distribution of $Q$ for random mass triples; the red line marks $Q = 2/3$. \emph{Right:} among random draws where $Q \approx 2/3$, the distribution of the best match between $L^2$ and any of six random quark masses (no running). The observed $0.10\%$ match (red dashed line) lies in the far left tail at $p = 0.004$.}
\label{fig:descartes}
\end{figure}


\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{What survives}

Three classes of claims survive at $p < 0.05$:
\begin{enumerate}
\item The original lepton Koide ($p = 0.006$): zero degrees of freedom.
\item Pre-specified single-triple claims with running ($p = 0.005$--$0.011$): the triple and sign pattern are specified before computation.
\item The Descartes/Soddy lepton-to-strange construction ($p = 0.004$--$0.012$): near-zero degrees of freedom due to the deterministic geometry.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{What does not survive}

Any claim that searches across multiple triples without pre-specification does not survive at $p < 0.05$ once running is included (Figure~\ref{fig:ranking}). The full 20-triple search at maximum freedom ($p = 0.49$) has no discriminating power.

\subsection{The role of running}

The evaluation-scale degree of freedom is the specific knob that degrades severity. Running allows each mass to be adjusted by up to $35\%$ (bottom at $M_W$ versus self-scale), which is sufficient for random triples to find $Q = 2/3$ by chance. At self-scale, even a 20-triple search retains $p = 0.21$; adding running drops it to $p = 0.49$.

This does not mean that evaluating quark masses at non-self scales is illegitimate---it is standard practice in QCD. It means that resulting closures must be evaluated against a higher noise floor.

\subsection{Limitations}

This analysis tests a specific set of formulations and search spaces. We have not tested Koide-type relations with different algebraic targets ($Q = 1/3$, $Q = 1/2$), relations involving neutrino or boson masses, continuous scale scanning, or alternative mass schemes. The severity estimates are specific to the search spaces defined here.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

The original Koide formula, the pre-specified $(c, b, t)$ heavy Koide closure, and the Descartes/Soddy lepton-to-strange construction are the only Koide-type mass relations that survive a severity analysis at $p < 0.05$ under the search spaces tested. Claims that search across multiple triples or use unconstrained evaluation-scale freedom do not survive. The evaluation-scale degree of freedom (QCD running) is the specific parameter that degrades test severity.

These results are presented as an inventory of what survives and what does not under the statistical framework applied here. Whether the surviving relations have physical significance beyond their statistical survival is a question this note does not attempt to answer.


\section*{Computational note}

All computations are reproducible from the accompanying repository~\citep{RepoMC}. The search space is defined in \texttt{search\_space.json}. Four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec}. FLAG~2024~\citep{FLAG2024} and PDG~2024~\citep{PDG2024} inputs. Monte Carlo pseudo-experiments use \texttt{numpy} random number generation with documented seeds.


